I am currently working on an graphical user interface for a program using Qt, this interface should be abstract.  
  
To do this I mainly use two classes, `QtUiFunctions` that uses Qt and contains basic functions such as `addButton` or `addShape` and `GUI` that doesn&#39;t use Qt directly but calls functions from `QtUiFunctions` 
 to do so and contains more complex functions such as `displayAuthWindow` or `displayMainWindow`.  
To be able to use functions to make a button they all have to be in the same class, the easiest was for them to not be in a class or be static.  
`GUI` contains a pointer to `QtUiFunctions` to be able to use said functions.  

My problem is that I have some buttons that call `displayAuthWindow` or `displayMainWindow` to switch between menus, those buttons call functions that make other buttons themselves.  
So these functions have to be static in order to be made into a button but if they are then they can&#39;t access the pointer to `QtUiFunctions` and make buttons themselves. 

I&#39;ve tried using templates to go around having to make my functions static but this is not possible because the function I would need to template is virtual.

